04818nam a22006975i 9780801454851DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20152016nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808014548517 a10.7591/97808014548512doi  a(DE-B1597)496505  a(OCoLC)1041979348  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aSCI0340002bisacsh04a001.09/0322231 aLipking, Lawrence, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWhat Galileo Saw :bImagining the Scientific Revolution /cLawrence Lipking. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2015] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (336 p.) :b7 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tChapter 1. Introducing A Revolution -- tChapter 2. What Galileo Saw -- tChapter 3. Kepler’s Progress -- tChapter 4. The Poetry Of The World -- tChapter 5. “Look There, Look There!” -- tChapter 6. The Dream Of Descartes -- tChapter 7. A History Of Error -- tChapter 8. The Century Of Genius (1) -- tChapter 9. The Century Of Genius (2) -- tChapter 10. Revolution And Its Discontents -- tAppendix 1. Galileo The Fable Of Sound -- tAppendix 2. Descartes’s Three Dreams -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Scientific Revolution of the seventeenth century has often been called a decisive turning point in human history. It represents, for good or ill, the birth of modern science and modern ways of viewing the world. In What Galileo Saw, Lawrence Lipking offers a new perspective on how to understand what happened then, arguing that artistic imagination and creativity as much as rational thought played a critical role in creating new visions of science and in shaping stories about eye-opening discoveries in cosmology, natural history, engineering, and the life sciences.When Galileo saw the face of the Moon and the moons of Jupiter, Lipking writes, he had to picture a cosmos that could account for them. Kepler thought his geometry could open a window into the mind of God. Francis Bacon's natural history envisioned an order of things that would replace the illusions of language with solid evidence and transform notions of life and death. Descartes designed a hypothetical "Book of Nature" to explain how everything in the universe was constructed. Thomas Browne reconceived the boundaries of truth and error. Robert Hooke, like Leonardo, was both researcher and artist; his schemes illuminate the microscopic and the macrocosmic. And when Isaac Newton imagined nature as a coherent and comprehensive mathematical system, he redefined the goals of science and the meaning of genius.What Galileo Saw bridges the divide between science and art; it brings together Galileo and Milton, Bacon and Shakespeare. Lipking enters the minds and the workshops where the Scientific Revolution was fashioned, drawing on art, literature, and the history of science to reimagine how perceptions about the world and human life could change so drastically, and change forever.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aLiterature and sciencexHistoryy17th century. 0aSciencexHistoryy17th century. 4aHistory Of Science. 4aHistory. 7aSCIENCE / History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066749340uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080145485140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801454851423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780801454851.jpg  a978-3-11-066749-3  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aE